#Text=VI
#Text=BUT he did not stay away .
#Text=He owned and lived in a small house up on the Rumson Road .

#Text=While the house was little more than a bungalow and had a simplicity that completely hid its rare good taste from the average observer , its grounds were the most spacious in that neighborhood of costly , showy houses set in grounds not much more extensive than a city building lot .
#Text=The grounds had been cleared and drained to drive out and to keep out the obnoxious insect life , but had been left a forest , concealing the house from the roads .
#Text=Stanley Baird was now stopping with Keith , and brought him along to the cottage by the sea every day .
#Text=The parties narrowed to the same four persons .
#Text=Mrs. Brindley seemed never to tire of talking to Keith -- or to tire of talking about him when the two men had left , late each night .

#Text=As for Stanley , he referred everything to Keith -- the weather prospects , where they should go for the day , what should be eaten and drunk , any point about politics or fashion , life or literature or what not , that happened to be discussed .
#Text=And he looked upon Donald 's monosyllabic reply to his inquiry as a final judgment , ending all possibility of argument .
#Text=Mildred held out long .

#Text=Then , in spite of herself , she began to yield , ceased to dislike him , found a kind of pleasure -- or , perhaps , fascinated interest -- in the nervousness his silent and indifferent presence caused her .

#Text=She liked to watch that immobile , perfect profile , neither young nor old , indeed not suggesting age in any degree , but only experience and knowledge -- and an infinite capacity for emotion , for passion even .
#Text=The dead-white color declared it had already been lived ; the brilliant , usually averted or veiled eyes asserted present vitality , pulsing under a calm surface .
#Text=One day when Stanley , in the manner of one who wishes a thing settled and settled right , said he would ask Donald Keith about it , Mildred , a little piqued , a little amused , retorted :
#Text=" And what will he answer ?
#Text=" And that 's quite enough , is n't it ? "
#Text=" But how do you know he 's as wise as he pretends ? "
#Text=" He does n't pretend to be anything or to know anything .
#Text=Cyrilla 's usually positive gray eyes looked vague .
#Text=She smiled .
#Text=" I never asked , " said she .
#Text=" I 've known him nearly three years , and it never occurred to me to ask , or to wonder .
#Text=And she did about an hour later , when they were in the surf together , with the other two out of earshot .
#Text=Said Stanley :
#Text=" He 's a lawyer , of course .

column3:
_	_	_	_

#Text= And what did he answer ? " asked Mildred .

column1: #Text=" Nothing ? "
#Text=" He said : ' I make all I want .

#Text= I suppose some woman -- some disappointment in love -- has killed ambition , and everything like that . "

column1: #Text=" I do n't think so , " replied Baird .
#Text=" The men who knew him as a boy say he was always as he is now .

#Text= Why did n't he stay ? " laughed Mildred .

column1: #Text=" That life would exactly suit him . "
#Text=" It did , " said Stanley .
#Text=" But his father died , and he had to come home and support his mother -- until she died .
